@c ================================================================================
@node Maps
@section Maps

A map is an unordered collection of keys without duplicates, each key having an associated value;
with efficient operations to add a key/value pair, remove a key with its value, and to retrieve the
value for a key.  Adding a key/value pair to a map that already contains it, or removing a key from
a map that does not contain it, result in the same map.

Although maps are conceptually unordered, FSet imposes an order for its own purposes.  The WB
implementation allows you to @href{Custom Comparison and Hash Functions, control} this ordering.

Maps have default values that are returned by a @code{lookup} on a key that is not in the map;
@pxref{Map and Seq Defaults}.

The default implementation of maps is currently CHAMP (@code{ch-map}).  The WB implementation
(@code{wb-map}) is also available.

The implementation-specific map constructor functions and macros accept two @href{Custom Comparison
and Hash Functions, comparison functions}, one for the keys and one for the values.  The importance
of the former should be obvious, but you might wonder why the latter is needed.  FSet uses it in a
few ways:

@itemize
@item
Detecting a redundant @code{with} operation, where the key/value pair being added is already in the
map

@item
Constructing the value of the @code{range} operation, that returns all the values as a set

@item
Constructing the result of @code{map-difference} and  @code{map-difference-2}
@end itemize

In most cases, you can just let the value comparison function default to @code{#'compare}.
Occasionally, though, you might need this:

@defun eql-compare a b
Returns @code{:equal} if @var{a} and @var{b} are equal by @code{eql}; otherwise @code{:unequal}.
This can be supplied as a value comparison function for a map when the range type is one not handled
by FSet, such as CL hash tables or function objects.  It is @emph{not recommended} for comparing set
or bag values or map keys, as it imposes no ordering, and its associated hash function always
returns 0; if you used it for one of those purposes, FSet would fall back to using lists with linear
search.
@end defun

@hrule{}

@deftp {Data type} map
The abstract class for FSet functional maps.
@end deftp

@defun empty-map @r{&key} @r{(@var{default} nil)} no-default?
Constructor function.  Returns an empty map of the default implementation and organization.  If
@var{default} is supplied, that will be the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default}; if
@var{no-default?} is true, the map will have no default.
@end defun

@defmac map @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a map of the default implementation according to the supplied
argument subforms.  Each argument subform can be a list of the form @code{(@var{key-expr}
@var{value-expr})}, denoting a mapping from the value of @var{key-expr} to the value of
@var{value-expr}; or a list of the form @code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression
must evaluate to a map, denoting all its mappings; or the symbol @code{:default}, followed by a
form; or the symbol @code{:no-default}.  If @code{:default} is supplied, the map's @href{Map and Seq
Defaults, default} is the value of the subsequent form; if @code{:no-default} is supplied, the map
has no default; if neither, the map's default is @code{nil}.

As a convenience, if a subform is @code{($ @var{expression})} and the expression evaluates to
@code{nil}, it will be treated as an empty map.  The result is constructed from the denoted mappings
in left-to-right order; so if a given key is supplied by more than one argument subform, its
associated value will be given by the rightmost such subform.
@end defmac

@deftp {Data type} ch-map
Functional maps implemented using CHAMP trees.  These print as:

@example
##@{| (@i{k0 v0}) (@i{k1 v1}) ... @}[@i{key-compare-fn};@i{val-compare-fn}]/@i{default}
@end example

Note the double @code{#}, which indicates CHAMP.  The comparison functions are printed only if they
are not @code{compare}.  The default is printed only if it is not @code{nil}; if the map has no
default, @code{/[no default]} is printed.
@end deftp

@defun empty-ch-map @r{&key} @r{(@var{default} nil)} no-default? key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name
Constructor function.  Returns an empty @code{ch-map}.  If @var{default} is supplied, that will be
the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default}; if @var{no-default?} is true, the map will have no
default.  @var{key-compare-fn-name} and @var{val-compare-fn-name} must be symbols naming the
comparison functions to be used for keys and values respectively (these default to
@code{#'compare}).  A hash function must have been defined for each comparison function using
@href{define-hash-function, @code{define-hash-function}}.
@end defun

@defmac ch-map @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-map} according to the supplied argument subforms.  Each
argument subform can be a list of the form @code{(@var{key-expr} @var{value-expr})}, denoting a
mapping from the value of @var{key-expr} to the value of @var{value-expr}; or a list of the form
@code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate to a map, denoting all its
mappings; or the symbol @code{:default}, followed by a form; or the symbol @code{:no-default}.  If
@code{:default} is supplied, the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default} is the value of the
subsequent form; if @code{:no-default} is supplied, the map has no default; if neither, the map's
default is @code{nil}.

As a convenience, if a subform is @code{($ @var{expression})} and the expression evaluates to
@code{nil}, it will be treated as an empty map.  The result is constructed from the denoted mappings
in left-to-right order; so if a given key is supplied by more than one argument subform, its
associated value will be given by the rightmost such subform.
@end defmac

@defmac ch-custom-map key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-map} with a custom organization according to the supplied
argument subforms.  @var{key-compare-fn-name} and @var{val-compare-fn-name} must be symbols naming
the comparison functions to be used for keys and values respectively (you can use @code{nil} as a
synonym of @code{compare}).  A hash function must have been defined for each comparison function
using @href{define-hash-function, @code{define-hash-function}}.

Each argument subform can be a list of the form @code{(@var{key-expr} @var{value-expr})}, denoting a
mapping from the value of @var{key-expr} to the value of @var{value-expr}; or a list of the form
@code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate to a map, denoting all its
mappings; or the symbol @code{:default}, followed by a form; or the symbol @code{:no-default}.  If
@code{:default} is supplied, the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default} is the value of the
subsequent form; if @code{:no-default} is supplied, the map has no default; if neither, the map's
default is @code{nil}.

As a convenience, if a subform is @code{($ @var{expression})} and the expression evaluates to
@code{nil}, it will be treated as an empty map.  The result is constructed from the denoted mappings
in left-to-right order; so if a given key is supplied by more than one argument subform, its
associated value will be given by the rightmost such subform.
@end defmac

@deftp {Data type} wb-map
Functional maps implemented using WB-trees.  These print as:

@example
#@{| (@i{k0 v0}) (@i{k1 v1}) @dots{} @}[@i{key-compare-fn};@i{val-compare-fn}]/@i{default}
@end example

Note the single @code{#}, which indicates WB.  The comparison functions are printed only if they are
not @code{compare}.  The default is printed only if it is not @code{nil}; if the map has no
default, @code{/[no default]} is printed.
@end deftp

@defun empty-wb-map @r{&key} @r{(@var{default} nil)} no-default? key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name
Constructor function.  Returns an empty map of the default implementation and organization.  If
@var{default} is supplied, that will be the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default}; if
@var{no-default?} is true, the map will have no default.  @var{key-compare-fn-name} and
@var{val-compare-fn-name} must be symbols naming the comparison functions to be used for keys and
values respectively (these default to @code{#'compare}).
@end defun

@defmac wb-map @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{wb-map} according to the supplied argument subforms.  Each
